<TEXT>
president bush in his first 
presidential address to the united nations will announce a major 
initiative to cut chemical weapons arsenals by more than 50 percent 
providing the soviet union do the same administration sources said 
sunday night 
the president in between church services fishing and golf 
worked with his national security adviser brent scowcroft and 
other aides sunday at his seaside vacation home to finish the 
speech to be delivered monday 
the central focus of the speech is to be a proposal that 
secretary of state james a baker iii said would move the world 
closer to a ban on chemical weapons 
it is part of a steppedup us drive to slow or even stop the 
spread of chemical weapons around the world 
baker informed soviet foreign minister eduard a shevardnadze of 
the presidents intention in their talks over the weekend in 
jackson hole wyo there the two sides agreed on a twostage 
ussoviet program to exchange information about their chemical 
weapons and to inspect each others plants and arsenals 
but the sources who spoke in new york on condition of 
anonymity said the superpowers were faced with the bigger problem 
of halting the spread of the weapons to other countries including 
in stabile regimes in the third world some two dozen countries are 
believed to possess chemical weapons or have the capacity to 
produce them 
first disclosure of bushs initiative came in mondays editions 
of the new york times the sources confirming the thrust of the 
newspapers account said bush also would suggest sanctions against 
countries which proceed with chemical weapons production 
the new york times said the united states was believed to have 
about 30000 tons of chemical weapons while the soviet union says 
it has 50000 tons western nations say the soviets actually may 
have more than 300000 tons 
the us proposal is intended to spur progress in negotiations 
in geneva where 40 nations are trying to reach a global agreement 
on chemical weapons 
one official traveling with the president described bushs 
proposal as a challenge to the soviet union to join the united 
states in action on chemical weapons 
another official called the plan a new initiative to move 
forward in elimination of chemical weapons to reduce stockpiles 
and generally try to give a new impetus to a total ban 
white house officials were tight lipped on what that proposal 
would contain 
the president has been concerned for a number of years about 
the horrors of chemical weapons he made a major presentation to 
the un conference in 1984 on the possibility of banning chemical 
weapons and he will have some proposals tomorrow to advance that 
issue scowcroft said sunday on the nbc show meet the press 
the united states and soviet union are the only two nations that 
admit to having chemical weapons stockpiles however us analysts 
estimate two dozen countries have the weapons or the capacity to 
produce them 
bushs speechwriters completed a draft of his un address 
saturday night following announcement of several accords and plans 
for a superpower summit as a result of two days of talks in 
wyoming between baker and soviet foreign minister eduard 
shevardnadze 
among the accords was an agreement to exchange data on chemical 
weapons by the end of the year and allow visits by inspectors of 
the other side to stockpiles and plants by june 30 in a second 
phase there would be more intensive onsite inspections of the 
submitted data 
in addition to the chemical weapons proposal scowcroft said 
the thrust of the un speech will be celebrating the march of 
democracy and freedom dealing with many of the multilateral issues 
affecting the world drugs terrorism environment 
the president is expected to include one of his favorite themes 
the moves toward political and economic reform in poland and other 
east bloc countries 
at the un where bush served as the us ambassador in 1971 
and 1972 the president will hold several bilateral meetings and 
will meet with un secretary general javier perez de cuellar 
he also will meet with brazils president jose sarney israeli 
deputy prime minister shimon peres guatemalan president vinicio 
cerezo venezuelan president carlos andres perez and bolivian 
president jaime paz zamora 
bush will host a lunch for nato allies and with his wife 
barbara also will visit the metropolitan museum of art for a 
diplomatic reception and dinner during their busy day in new york 
cramming in as much recreation as possible before heading to new 
york monday morning bush pitched horseshoes sunday along with 
golfing and fishing 
</TEXT>
