the united states and other rich industrial 
countries will experience a healthy cooling of business growth this 
year and next the international monetary fund predicted sunday 
projections point to a gradual moderation in the pace of 
expansion during 1989 and 1990 following two years of rapid 
growth the fund said in its semiannual world economic 
outlook 
for this year it sees the united states and 20 other 
noncommunist industrial countries increasing their total output by 
35 percent that is 02 percent higher than its prediction of last 
april though the fraction seems in percentage terms the 
difference amounts to tens of billions of dollars worth of 
additional goods and services for the group 
in 1990 growth is predicted to be 29 percent for the 21 
countries 
for the united states alone the worlds biggest economy the 
slowdown is seen as much greater 44 percent last year 29 
percent this year and only 21 percent in 1990 
the most growth is predicted for japan 49 percent this year 
and 47 percent in 1990 for west germany 4 percent and 3 percent 
for france 34 and 3 for italy 32 and 29 and for britain 3 and 
27 
there is no sign of recession we do not see it in the 
current projections jacob frenkel the funds research chief 
told reporters 
he called the slowdown healthy and said he was especially 
cheered by the growth of investment in new plants and equipment 
these create additional jobs and production for the future 
