<TEXT>
reformist politburo member imre pozsgay 
said sunday the ruling hungarian socialist workers party will no 
longer be considered a communist party the official mti news 
agency reported 
pozsgay a leading reformer who is also one of the countrys 
fourmember leadership said the change would take effect after a 
party congress next month he also said he would quit the party 
should its reform wing be defeated at the congress which begins 
oct 6 
although officially designated socialist the party took 
power in 194748 as the hungarian communist party it was renamed 
and reorganized in the wake of the 1956 popular uprising that was 
crushed by soviet tanks and troops 
mti paraphrasing pozsgays comments in an interview with 
italian television quoted him as saying that after the congress 
the socialist workers party will call itself simply a socialist 
party and will no longer be a communist party in the bolshevik 
and stalinist sense of the word 
pozsgay has been at the forefront of political change in 
hungary he was among the first officials to publicly declare that 
the 1956 events were not a counterrevolution but a popular movement 
in numerous interviews pozsgay has insisted there is no 
alternative to hungary becoming a multiparty democracy 
in our endeavors we feel related to the socialist parties of 
western europe pozsgay was quoted as saying of the party 
should the reformers not win at the congress next month which 
would imply a halt to party reforms he would not remain in an 
obsolete organization pozsgay was quoted as saying 
in its session tuesday parliament will discuss and vote on key 
legislation for hungarys transformation into a multiparty state 
the first free elections since the communist takeover will be held 
by june 1990 
draft laws before parliament include constitutional changes a 
law on the activity of political parties the establishment of a 
constitutional court an electoral law a change in the penal code 
and in criminal proceedings 
those legislative items were agreed upon after negotiations 
between the ruling communists and the political opposition 
also under hungarys political reforms in midseptember 
budapest opened its borders with austria allowing more than 17000 
east german refugees to flee to the west 
</TEXT>
