<TEXT>
international conferences have failed to stop 
production of chemical weapons which could be made and used by 
terrorists the editor of an industry yearbook said monday 
verification is one of the main stumbling blocks to any proposed 
ban on chemical weapons because they can be made in commercial 
factories or backroom workshops terry gander said 
gander is editor of the second volume of the authoritative 
yearbook janes nbc nuclear biological and chemical protection 
equipment published monday 
on a small scale it could be possible to produce lethal 
agents in backroom workshops and it would only take a few 
smallscale uses of the resultant chemical weapons to run a 
railroad through any treaty gander said 
as yet none of the numerous terrorist groups that infest the 
modern world have turned their attention to the possible uses of 
chemical warfare but the potential for them to do so has been 
around for a very long time he said it could be stated that 
the actual event of such an attack taking place can only be a 
matter of by whom when and where 
ganders warning was written ahead of the weekend agreement by 
us secretary of state james a baker iii and soviet foreign 
minister eduard a shevardnadze to exchange data on chemical 
weapons and to inspect each others stockpiles and plants 
gander said the 40nation conference on disarmament in geneva 
has progressed toward some form of ban on chemical weapons it but 
keeps stumbling over the verification problem 
the disarmament conference has been debating a global convention 
outlawing the production stockpiling and use of chemical arms 
since 1968 
policing and supervising every peaceful commercial plant which 
could also be used to produce chemical weapons would be a vast and 
almost impossible task even using satellite surveillance gander 
said 
gander also warned that recent advances in genetic and related 
technologies mean that biological warfare is a distinct 
possibility in the very near future 
several major powers have openly renounced all possible use of 
such weapons but the danger still lurks that some nations would be 
only too happy to employ biological weapons to further their own 
ends in some future conflict he said 
