<TEXT>
a reformist bloc in the soviet parliament adopted 
a platform sunday that calls for allowing ownership of private 
property prices set by market conditions and television free of 
government control 
the first platform of the 345 reformminded deputies from the 
soviet parliament will be put beforethe 542member supreme soviet 
which convenes a new legislative session on monday 
the reformist bloc members of the 2250member parliament 
also have drafted a bill that they say could lead to the formation 
of noncommunist political parties 
the platform places emphasis on new laws to guarantee human 
rights it includes the freedom to publish to strike and to move 
soviets currently must carry internal passports and obtain 
permission to move into desired urban areas such as moscow and the 
government still denies external passports to many citizens 
sergei stankevich a leader of the reformist bloc called the 
interregional group said he and others have written a bill 
already approved by a subcommittee that would guarantee the right 
to form organizations he said people could use this legal 
protection to form noncommunist political parties 
stankevich warned that the proposal would face a sharp 
discussion rather than sail easily through the legislature 
elements of the bill also are included in the groups platform 
which was adopted overwhelmingly on sunday 
i dont think it will change our political conditions 
immediately or drastically he said 
the platform of the reform coalition which includes populist 
boris yeltsin and human rights activist andrei sakharov also calls 
for eliminating a provision in the soviet constitution that defines 
the communist party as the leading force in society 
the group suggests substituting a phrase defining the 
soviets elected bodies from the level of city council to 
national parliament as the only source of political power 
the supreme soviet or legislature on monday opens its second 
session since the nations first multicandidate elections were 
held last spring in the opening session deputies held the 
nations first confirmation hearings on cabinetlevel jobs and 
forced the withdrawal of a number of candidates 
however deputies are only now organizing sufficiently to offer 
their own bills to compete with those proposed by the kremlin 
president mikhail s gorbachev is to open the session with a 
speech topping the enormous agenda of 80 reform bills is a package 
aimed at easing the disastrous economic situation which has 
stripped store shelves nearly bare and left much of the nation 
relying on ration coupons for key food items 
the government plan calls for slashing the budget deficit from 
120 billion rubles 186 billion to 60 billion rubles 93 
billion and the leasing of many factories and much farmland to 
individuals and groups 
the interregional group is calling for legalization of private 
property and the introduction of market pricing gorbachevs 
advisers also have promoted letting supply and demand set prices 
but in the face of strong public objection to lifting government 
subsidies the government has promised to delay the proposal for 
several years 
the opposition group proposed that the vast industrial 
ministries which now control the supplies and decisions of most 
factories in the country should be replaced with small commissions 
of experts in the field 
the group also called for an end to the government monopoly on 
television a call reminiscent of last weeks decision of the new 
government in poland to take control of its government television 
away from the communist party 
several members of the interregional group said their platform 
included only a fraction of the critical reforms needed but 
historian yuri afansiev argued that they were adopting only their 
first working paper setting the groups general orientation he 
said it would be refined and expanded later 
